    {
      "id": "f0b04b9b17fcb00e0c99c41116c239c78660eadf",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-09-29 20:40:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nFrank, are you certain these two \"do the same thing\" here?  __l_wait_event is a really complex (and horrible) macro.\n\nAt the least, the two have different behavior with regards to signal handling.  __l_wait_event blocks all signals when it has a timeout, wait_event_timeout does not.  In this case, I think both wait in TASK_UNINTERRUPTIBLE, so the blocking of all signals should be irrelevant...\n\nI admit, I can't find a specific difference between using the two macros in this instance, but they certainly aren't equivalent in the general case.  The LWI passed to l_wait_event allows for a really broad range of behavior.\n\nGiven that, are you sure they're equivalent here?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4987d8b8cc239f48ee896283041577e32bc55126",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 419,
        "name": "Frank Zago",
        "email": "fzago@cray.com",
        "username": "fzago.cray"
      },
      "date": "2016-09-29 20:47:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis series of patches has been failing test 28 many times, which I've never been able to reproduce on my test VMs. So I'm trying different approaches. I feel the same as you about l_wait_event, which is why I think that could be part of the issue, and for the usage at hand I think it's the same as wait_event.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e80e951b1fb8b80e0ccfdd4ce25974381e723af0",
      "author": {
